There are currently no commercial options to return to the UK from Sudan. Since 16 March, all international passenger flights to and from Sudan have been suspended. Cargo flights are permitted, but crew must observe strict guidelines. Land borders and seaports are also closed, except for food and aid transport.
The UK government has facilitated a special flight from Khartoum to the UK departing on 21 May. This flight is now full and the booking portal is closed. Tickets will not be on sale at the airport. You should not travel to the airport without a confirmed ticket.
If you have registered for the special flight on 21 May 2020
If you have registered for the flight on 21 May you will receive an email confirming whether you have been allocated a seat or not at least 24 hours before the flight. If you are allocated a seat you will receive an email with all the details you need including what time to be at the airport. You must print and take your confirmed itinerary with you to the airport. A copy on a smart phone or similar is also sufficient.
You will be notified if you have not been allocated a seat, and will need to request a refund from CTM, which you should receive within 14 days.
If you have an urgent question about this flight please contact stayincontactsudan@fco.gov.uk
Travel to the airport for the special flight on 21 May
You are responsible for your travel to the airport. The timing of the flight is planned to allow travel to the airport during the morning. The Embassy will issue a standard letter the day before the flight which can be shown if you are stopped at checkpoints. The letter will provide confirmation of your seat on the flight and requests the authorities to allow you to travel to the airport. Further details will be provided once your booking is confirmed.
Your journey home
The National Travel Health Network and Centre (NaTHNaC) provides advice on how to stay safe as you travel by air.
When you arrive back in the UK, follow the guidance for when you return to the UK on steps you should take to protect yourself and others.
Help and support
If you need urgent consular assistance, you can contact the British Embassy on +249 156 77 55 00, and choose the option for consular assistance.
The Embassy cannot provide further information or advice about departure options over the phone. This page will be updated when departure options become available and, if you are registered with the Embassy, we will alert you by email. To get the latest information sign up for travel advice email alerts.
What to do
If you cannot leave Sudan at this time, see advice on staying in Sudan during coronavirus.
If you are a British national in Sudan and wish to register your intention to return to the UK, please email the details listed below to our dedicated mailbox at stayincontactsudan@fco.gov.uk. Register your details with us even if you have previously been in contact so that we have the information listed below:
your full name as shown on your passport
passport number
date of birth
place of residence in UK
where exactly you are currently staying in Sudan
email address and telephone number (please ensure that you are able to receive phone calls from unidentified numbers, including internationally, in case we need to reach you)
any specific medical needs/vulnerabilities
evidence of your return journey to the UK, eg an itinerary or confirmed flight booking that you were unable to use or is imminent
copy of the details page of your passport
You should also provide this information for any family members with you in Sudan that are also seeking to return to the UK.
